          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":40,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"days\":[{\"day_of_week\":0,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"Easy long run at 5:50–6:27/km. Keep effort conversational throughout. Target 14 km — matching your current long run distance to establish the baseline before we build. This is about time on feet, not pace.\"},{\"day_of_week\":1,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest day. Recovery is where adaptation happens — this is an active investment in Sunday's effort.\"},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"Easy aerobic run at 5:50–6:27/km, 8 km. Focus on relaxed form and breathing. A great day to tune into how your body is responding to the week's first effort.\"},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"slot_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"notes\":\"Low-impact cross-training: cycling, swimming, or yoga. 30–45 minutes. Given your IT band history, this is a smart way to build aerobic capacity without adding run-specific load.\"},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"notes\":\"Threshold run: 2 km easy warm-up, 3×8 min at 4:50/km with 90 sec easy jog recovery, 2 km easy cool-down (~10 km total). This is your first taste of half-marathon specific work — threshold pace trains your lactate clearance, which is the engine behind a 1:45 finish.\"},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. Two quality sessions this week (long run + tempo) means your body needs this. Trust the process.\"},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"Easy recovery run at 5:50–6:27/km, 8 km. Keep it genuinely easy — this is flushing, not training. If you feel flat, that's normal mid-week.\"}],\"week_summary\":\"Welcome to your half-marathon build, Lee. Week 1 is about establishing a solid, sustainable foundation. Your recent training shows you've been running 28–34 km over 3–4 days, so we're starting right at your current volume (40 km) to honour where you actually are — not where the plan wants you to be. The week includes one quality session (Thursday tempo) and a long run at your current distance, with cross-training on Wednesday to protect that IT band history. Your VDOT of 42.0 puts a 1:45 half-marathon well within reach with consistent, smart training over the next 16 weeks. The paces above are derived directly from your 48:00 10K — trust them, especially on easy days when they might feel slower than expected. That's exactly right.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
